WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that formalizes the representation, transformation, and
perceptual evaluation of color in digital imaging. It defines the
ACES 2.0 framework, gamut compression algorithms, Dolby Vision 2.0,
the ST.2084 PQ EOTF, advanced color difference metrics, camera
color DNA, spectral LUT modeling, white point adaptation, and skin
tone fairness constraints. It is the normative layer that ensures
color, from capture to display, is scientifically traceable and
artistically consistent.

WHY IT EXISTS
Color is the emotional carrier of the image. Without a rigorous,
perceptually uniform framework, the same RGB triplet can appear
different on two displays, a grade can shift between suites, and
skin tones can become distorted. This kingdom provides the single
source of truth for all color transforms, replacing proprietary
color science with an open, auditable protocol that honours the
CIE and ACES standards.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Eight sub-domains: ACES 2.0 Framework, Advanced Gamut Compression,
Dolby Vision 2.0 and ST.2084 PQ, Human Visual System Modeling for
Color, Advanced Color Metrics, Camera Color Science DNA, Spectral
LUT and 31-Band Modeling, and White Point Adaptation with Skin Tone
Fairness. Each section delivers the defining formulas and the
perceptual rationale behind them.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
On-set color management (IDT and LMT), DI grading (ACEScct working
space), mastering for HDR (Dolby Vision trim passes), display
calibration, VFX compositing (ACEScg linear space), AI training
data linearization, and automated quality control (DeltaE2000,
CAM16-UCS metrics).

WHO USES IT
Color scientists, finishing colorists, DITs, pipeline engineers
implementing OCIO configs, and anyone responsible for color
fidelity across the imaging chain.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Eradicates inconsistent color by providing a single mathematical
